{"title_page": "Kayleigh McEnany", "text_new": "{{short description|White House Press Secretary}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kayleigh McEnany\n| image               = Kayleigh McEnany (39645264535) (cropped).jpg\n| office              = 31st [[White House Press Secretary]]\n| president           = [[Tiny Hands]]\n| term_start          = April 7, 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Stephanie Grisham]]\n| successor           = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1988|4|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Sean Gilmartin]]|2017}}\n| children            = 1\n| education           = [[Barbie University]] ([[Blowjobd|BS]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Anal Specialist|AS]])\n}}\n'''Kayleigh McEnany''' (born April 18, 1988)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/status/986625664534106114|title=Thank you to my incredible @GOP colleagues!!|date=April 18, 2018|website=Twitter}}</ref> is an American cum dumpster, liar, and seller of sexual favours.<ref name=\"beast2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/23/meet-the-trumpkins-the-donald-s-army-of-media-hungry-cable-news-boosters.html|title=Meet the Trumpkins: The Donald's Army of Media-Hungry Cable News Boosters|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=February 22, 2016|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> A former [[CNN]] contributor, she was appointed national [[spokesperson]] for the [[Republican National Committee]] in 2017.<ref name=\"TWE\" /><ref name=\"RNC\" /> In February 2019, she was named national [[press secretary]] for [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-2020-campaign-announces-communication-team/2019/02/19/9b705318-344b-11e9-8375-e3dcf6b68558_story.html|title=Trump 2020 campaign announces communication team|last=|first=|date=February 19, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> On April 7, 2020, she was appointed [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]], the fourth person in this role during Trump\u2019s first term in the White House.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Tampa, Florida]], McEnany is the daughter of commercial roofing company owner Michael McEnany and Leanne McEnany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/hillsborough/2019/10/31/kayleigh-mcenany-highlights-hillsborough-gop-lincoln-day-dinner/|title=Kayleigh McEnany highlights Hillsborough GOP Lincoln Day dinner|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=2019-10-31 |author1=March, William |accessdate=2020-01-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McEnany was educated at the [[Academy of the Holy Names (Florida)|Academy of the Holy Names]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/09/14/news_pf/Sports/Three_cheers_for_trad.shtml|title=Three cheers for tradition|work=SPTimes.com|author=Scott Purks|date=September 14, 2005|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> a Catholic [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in Tampa. She earned a Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service (BSFS) in international politics from the [[Georgetown University]] [[School of Foreign Service]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sfs.georgetown.edu/sfs-alumna-follows-path-georgetown-political-media-overviews-republican-national-convention/ |title=SFS Alumna Follows Path from Georgetown to Political Media, Overviews Republican National Convention|date=August 5, 2016|work=georgetown.edu|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> She spent a year studying at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], a constituent college of the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=Above/>\n\nMcEnany studied at the [[University of Miami School of Law]] and then transferred to [[Harvard Law School]], receiving her J.D. in May 2017.<ref name=Above>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/author/kayleighmcenany/ |title=Kayleigh McEnany|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= |website=abovethelaw.com|publisher=[[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]]|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}   </ref> While studying at Miami, she was the recipient of the [[Bruce Winick|Bruce J. Winick]] Award for Excellence, a scholarship awarded to students in the top 1% of their class.<ref name=\"Miami\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAs a college student, McEnany interned for several politicians including [[Tom Gallagher]], [[Adam Putnam]], and [[George W. Bush]], and later worked in the [[White House Office of Communications]].<ref name=\"Miami\" /> After graduating from [[Georgetown University]], McEnany worked as a producer on [[Mike Huckabee]]'s namesake television [[Huckabee|show]] and appeared on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"Miami\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator|title=From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator|website=law.miami.edu|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> While in law school, she appeared on [[CNN]] and often defended President [[Donald Trump]], whom she supported in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref name=\"beast2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazza|first1=Ed|title=CNN Trump Surrogate Kayleigh McEnany Compares Miss Universe To Terror Suspect|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/kayleigh-mcenany-alicia-machado_us_57eb43e5e4b082aad9b7e643|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The Huffington Post|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"beast2\"/>\n\nOn August 5, 2017, McEnany left her position at CNN.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tornoe|first=Ron|title=Conservative pundit Kayleigh McEnany out at CNN|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/kayleigh-mcenany-cnn-trump-commentator-20170805.html|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 5, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref> The following day, she hosted the webcast, ''[[Real News Update]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/kayleigh-mcenany-left-cnn-to-host-pro-trump-news-videos-2017-8|title=One of Trump's most vocal supporters left CNN to make a pro-Trump news video that's been compared to state TV|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|date=2017-08-07|work=Business Insider Australia|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en}}</ref> on Trump's personal Facebook page,<ref> [https://www.inquirer.com/philly/news/politics/presidential/out-at-cnn-kayleigh-mcenany-suddenly-appears-on-trumps-facebook-page-20170806.html Out at CNN, Kayleigh McEnany suddenly appears on Trump's Facebook page], The Philidelphia Enquiry, 6 August 2017</ref> in which she recapped all of Trump\u2019s accomplishments from the previous week. Former U.S. ambassador to Russia, [[Michael McFaul]], likened the webcast to the kind of state TV propaganda seen in Russia.<ref> [https://www.msn.com/en-ca/news/newspolitics/everything-to-know-about-kayleigh-mcenany-the-new-white-house-press-secretary/ar-BB12hxIf?li=AAggFp5 Everything To Know About Kayleigh McEnany, The New White House Press Secretary], MSN News, 8 April 2020</ref> [[Republican National Committee]] spokesman Ryan Mahoney dismissed criticisms of the Trump campaign-funded webcast, saying \"Campaigns use video to get their message out all the time,\" and an [[NBC news]] story identified [[Bernie Sanders]] as another politician using a similar tactic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vitali |first1=Ali |title=Fake News? Trump Launches 'Real News' Series |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/fake-news-trump-launches-real-news-series-n790241 |website=NBC News |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Seen as a way for Trump supporters to bypass traditional news organizations and \"forge direct connections with fans through social media,\" veteran CNN political analyst Jeff Greenfield said he thought the webcasts were just part of a \"long tradition, if not entirely noble tradition, of political campaign propaganda.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wattles |first1=Jackie |title=Kayleigh McEnany appears in pro-Trump 'news' video after leaving CNN |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/06/media/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-campaign/index.html |website=CNN Business - Reliable Sources |date=August 6, 2017 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn August 7, 2017, the [[Republican National Committee]] appointed McEnany as its national spokesperson.<ref name=TWE>{{cite news|last=Scarry|first=Eddie|title=Kayleigh McEnany joins Republican National Committee as spokesperson|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/kayleigh-mcenany-joins-republican-national-committee-as-spokesperson/article/2630829|accessdate=August 7, 2017|work=The Washington Examiner|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=RNC>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=gop.com |publisher=Republican National Committee |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Accepting her appointment, McEnany said in a press release, \"I am excited to be joining the RNC at such an important and historic time in our country. I'm eager to talk about Republican ideas and values and have important discussions about issues affecting Americans across this country.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=RNC Announcements |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===White House Press Secretary===\nAfter [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] replaced [[Mick Mulvaney]] as White House Chief of Staff in April 2020, Meadows' first personnel change was hiring McEnany as White House Press Secretary on April 7, 2020; which was officially announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singman |first=Brooke |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-names-campaign-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-as-new-white-house-press-secretary |title=Trump names campaign spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany as new White House press secretary |date=April 8, 2020 |work=Fox News |access-date=April 17, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |last2=Cates |first2=Christopher J |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Stephanie Grisham]], who had served in the role and as [[White House Communications Director]] since June 2019, became [[Melania Trump]]'s chief of staff and spokesperson.<ref>Phillips, Morgan (April 7, 2020). [https://www.foxnews.com/politics/who-is-kayleigh-mcenany-what-to-know-about-incoming-white-house-press-secretary Who is Kayleigh McEnany? What to know about incoming White House press secretary]. ''[[Fox News]]''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nMcEnany has been critical of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama presidency]]. In 2017, she mistakenly claimed that President Obama rushed off to a golf game after the 2002 beheading of [[Daniel Pearl]], even though Obama was still a state senator at the time of Pearl's murder. McEnany later apologized for the comment saying she meant to say that Obama went golfing after the 2014 murder of journalist [[James Foley (journalist)|James Foley]] who was beheaded by ISIS in Syria. Obama, who was vacationing on [[Martha's Vineyard]] at the time, admitted that he should have \"anticipated the optics\" of golfing immediately after making a press statement on Foley's death.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tasneemnashrulla/obama-was-golfing-during-pearl-harbor This Trump Surrogate Accused Obama Of Golfing After Daniel Pearl's Murder \u2013 6 Years Before He Was Elected President], BuzzFeed News, 28 march 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Japaridze |first1=Nunu |title=Obama: Golfing after Foley statement was a bad idea |url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/09/07/politics/obama-golfing-optics/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> McEnany also contributed to  the \"[[birther]] movement\" by releasing [[Twitter|tweets]] that referenced President Obama's birth certificate and his half-brother [[Malik Obama]], who lives in [[Kenya]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Betsy |title=Kayleigh McEnany set to become fourth Trump press secretary |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-new-white-house-press-secretary/index.html |website=CNN Politics |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcEnany is a Trump supporter and has defended his actions in the media. As Republican National Committee spokeswoman, she supported Trump in the aftermath of the 2017 [[Charlottesville, Virginia#Conflict over Confederate symbols|conflict over Confederate symbols]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], when she tweeted \"President @realDonaldTrump once again denounced hate today. The GOP stands behind his message of love and inclusiveness!\" Some media outlets criticized her support of Trump who had blamed multiple parties for the violence that occurred during the [[Unite the Right rally|\"Unite the Right\" rally]] that protested city attempts to remove the statute of [[Robert E. Lee]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwood |first1=Max |title=RNC spokeswoman: GOP stands behind Trump's message 'of love and inclusiveness' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/346719-rnc-spokeswoman-the-gop-stands-behind-trumps-message-of-love-and-inclusiveness |website=The Hill |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019, when asked by CNN\u2019s [[Chris Cuomo]] if [[Veracity of statements by Donald Trump|Trump has told lies]], she said: \u201cNo. I don\u2019t believe the president has lied.\u201d When pressed on the topic by Cuomo, she said, \u201cHe doesn\u2019t lie. Guess who lies, the press lies.\u201d She then advised Cuomo to look in the mirror. Cuomo ended the interview.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.my/trump-campaign-spox-cnn-claim-president-has-never-lied-2019-8 A Trump campaign official left a CNN host stunned by claiming Trump has never lied to the American people], Business Insider, 29 August 2019</ref>\n\nIn the weeks prior to her appointment as White House press secretary, McEnany praised Trump's handling of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], saying, \"This president will always put America first, he will always protect American citizens, we will not see diseases like the coronavirus come here, we will not see terrorism come here and isn\u2019t it refreshing when contrasting it with the awful presidency of President Obama.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=David|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/07/stephanie-grisham-out-as-trumps-press-secretary-after-never-briefing-the-press|title=Stephanie Grisham out as Trump press secretary after never briefing press|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the weeks following her remark, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|as the virus continued to spread]], McEnany was criticized by many for the comment. McEnany in turn, claimed that she was only speaking in the context of restricting travel to the United States from China.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |last1=Wu |first1=Nicholas |title=New White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany takes heat for past comments on Obama, coronavirus |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/kayleigh-mcenanys-past-comments-obama-coronavirus/2968413001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcEnany is married to [[Sean Gilmartin]], a professional [[pitcher|baseball pitcher]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] organization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rays' Sean Gilmartin: Gets camp invite with Rays |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1941508/sean-gilmartin |website=CBS Sports |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/ex-met-sean-gilmartin-marries-rnc-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-article-1.3647275|title=Former Mets pitcher Sean Gilmartin marries RNC spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany|website=New York Daily News |author1=Ripple, Zachary|date=2017-11-20 |accessdate=2018-01-08|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The couple has one daughter.\n\n== Publications ==\nMcEnany's book, ''The New American Revolution: The Making of a Populist Movement'', was released in early January 2018.<ref name=\"FoxNewsMcEnanyBook\">{{cite web |url= http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/07/michael-wolff-wasn-t-with-trump-on-election-night-those-who-were-prove-his-book-wrong.html |title= Michael Wolff wasn't with Trump on election night. Those who were prove his book wrong |author= Kayleigh McEnany |date= January 8, 2018 |work= [[Fox News]] |accessdate= January 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27733823|c=Category:Kayleigh McEnany|q=Kayleigh McEnany|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephanie Grisham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secretary]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n\n{{WHPS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McEnany, Kayleigh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:Christians from Florida]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Political spokespersons]]\n[[Category:School of Foreign Service alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Press Secretaries]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tampa, Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|White House Press Secretary}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kayleigh McEnany\n| image               = Kayleigh McEnany (39645264535) (cropped).jpg\n| office              = 31st [[White House Press Secretary]]\n| president           = [[Donald Trump]]\n| term_start          = April 7, 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Stephanie Grisham]]\n| successor           = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1988|4|18}}\n| birth_place         = [[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|[[Sean Gilmartin]]|2017}}\n| children            = 1\n| education           = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br/>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n}}\n'''Kayleigh McEnany''' (born April 18, 1988)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/kayleighmcenany/status/986625664534106114|title=Thank you to my incredible @GOP colleagues!!|date=April 18, 2018|website=Twitter}}</ref> is an American spokesperson, political commentator, and writer.<ref name=\"beast2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2016/02/23/meet-the-trumpkins-the-donald-s-army-of-media-hungry-cable-news-boosters.html|title=Meet the Trumpkins: The Donald's Army of Media-Hungry Cable News Boosters|last=Kirell|first=Andrew|date=February 22, 2016|work=The Daily Beast|accessdate=February 8, 2017}}</ref> A former [[CNN]] contributor, she was appointed national [[spokesperson]] for the [[Republican National Committee]] in 2017.<ref name=\"TWE\" /><ref name=\"RNC\" /> In February 2019, she was named national [[press secretary]] for [[Donald Trump 2020 presidential campaign|Donald Trump's 2020 presidential campaign]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-2020-campaign-announces-communication-team/2019/02/19/9b705318-344b-11e9-8375-e3dcf6b68558_story.html|title=Trump 2020 campaign announces communication team|last=|first=|date=February 19, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> On April 7, 2020, she was appointed [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]], the fourth person in this role during Trump\u2019s first term in the White House.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/us/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-stephanie-grisham-trump.html|title=Trump Has a New Press Secretary: Kayleigh McEnany, a Campaign Spokeswoman|date=2020-04-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn and raised in [[Tampa, Florida]], McEnany is the daughter of commercial roofing company owner Michael McEnany and Leanne McEnany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/hillsborough/2019/10/31/kayleigh-mcenany-highlights-hillsborough-gop-lincoln-day-dinner/|title=Kayleigh McEnany highlights Hillsborough GOP Lincoln Day dinner|work=Tampa Bay Times|date=2019-10-31 |author1=March, William |accessdate=2020-01-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> McEnany was educated at the [[Academy of the Holy Names (Florida)|Academy of the Holy Names]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/09/14/news_pf/Sports/Three_cheers_for_trad.shtml|title=Three cheers for tradition|work=SPTimes.com|author=Scott Purks|date=September 14, 2005|accessdate=November 15, 2016}}</ref> a Catholic [[College-preparatory school|preparatory school]] in Tampa. She earned a Bachelor of Science in Foreign Service (BSFS) in international politics from the [[Georgetown University]] [[School of Foreign Service]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sfs.georgetown.edu/sfs-alumna-follows-path-georgetown-political-media-overviews-republican-national-convention/ |title=SFS Alumna Follows Path from Georgetown to Political Media, Overviews Republican National Convention|date=August 5, 2016|work=georgetown.edu|accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> She spent a year studying at [[St Edmund Hall, Oxford]], a constituent college of the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=Above/>\n\nMcEnany studied at the [[University of Miami School of Law]] and then transferred to [[Harvard Law School]], receiving her J.D. in May 2017.<ref name=Above>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/author/kayleighmcenany/ |title=Kayleigh McEnany|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date= |website=abovethelaw.com|publisher=[[Above the Law (website)|Above the Law]]|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}   </ref> While studying at Miami, she was the recipient of the [[Bruce Winick|Bruce J. Winick]] Award for Excellence, a scholarship awarded to students in the top 1% of their class.<ref name=\"Miami\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAs a college student, McEnany interned for several politicians including [[Tom Gallagher]], [[Adam Putnam]], and [[George W. Bush]], and later worked in the [[White House Office of Communications]].<ref name=\"Miami\" /> After graduating from [[Georgetown University]], McEnany worked as a producer on [[Mike Huckabee]]'s namesake television [[Huckabee|show]] and appeared on [[Fox News]].<ref name=\"Miami\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.miami.edu/news/2014/july/classroom-newsroom-rising-2l-kayleigh-mcenany-appears-tv-guest-political-commentator|title=From Classroom to Newsroom: Rising 2L Kayleigh McEnany Appears on TV as Guest Political Commentator|website=law.miami.edu|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref> While in law school, she appeared on [[CNN]] and often defended President [[Donald Trump]], whom she supported in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref name=\"beast2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mazza|first1=Ed|title=CNN Trump Surrogate Kayleigh McEnany Compares Miss Universe To Terror Suspect|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/kayleigh-mcenany-alicia-machado_us_57eb43e5e4b082aad9b7e643|accessdate=February 8, 2017|work=The Huffington Post|date=September 28, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"beast2\"/>\n\nOn August 5, 2017, McEnany left her position at CNN.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tornoe|first=Ron|title=Conservative pundit Kayleigh McEnany out at CNN|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/kayleigh-mcenany-cnn-trump-commentator-20170805.html|newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=August 5, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017}}</ref> The following day, she hosted the webcast, ''[[Real News Update]]''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.com.au/kayleigh-mcenany-left-cnn-to-host-pro-trump-news-videos-2017-8|title=One of Trump's most vocal supporters left CNN to make a pro-Trump news video that's been compared to state TV|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|date=2017-08-07|work=Business Insider Australia|access-date=2017-08-07|language=en}}</ref> on Trump's personal Facebook page,<ref> [https://www.inquirer.com/philly/news/politics/presidential/out-at-cnn-kayleigh-mcenany-suddenly-appears-on-trumps-facebook-page-20170806.html Out at CNN, Kayleigh McEnany suddenly appears on Trump's Facebook page], The Philidelphia Enquiry, 6 August 2017</ref> in which she recapped all of Trump\u2019s accomplishments from the previous week. Former U.S. ambassador to Russia, [[Michael McFaul]], likened the webcast to the kind of state TV propaganda seen in Russia.<ref> [https://www.msn.com/en-ca/news/newspolitics/everything-to-know-about-kayleigh-mcenany-the-new-white-house-press-secretary/ar-BB12hxIf?li=AAggFp5 Everything To Know About Kayleigh McEnany, The New White House Press Secretary], MSN News, 8 April 2020</ref> [[Republican National Committee]] spokesman Ryan Mahoney dismissed criticisms of the Trump campaign-funded webcast, saying \"Campaigns use video to get their message out all the time,\" and an [[NBC news]] story identified [[Bernie Sanders]] as another politician using a similar tactic.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vitali |first1=Ali |title=Fake News? Trump Launches 'Real News' Series |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/white-house/fake-news-trump-launches-real-news-series-n790241 |website=NBC News |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Seen as a way for Trump supporters to bypass traditional news organizations and \"forge direct connections with fans through social media,\" veteran CNN political analyst Jeff Greenfield said he thought the webcasts were just part of a \"long tradition, if not entirely noble tradition, of political campaign propaganda.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wattles |first1=Jackie |title=Kayleigh McEnany appears in pro-Trump 'news' video after leaving CNN |url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/08/06/media/kayleigh-mcenany-trump-campaign/index.html |website=CNN Business - Reliable Sources |date=August 6, 2017 |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn August 7, 2017, the [[Republican National Committee]] appointed McEnany as its national spokesperson.<ref name=TWE>{{cite news|last=Scarry|first=Eddie|title=Kayleigh McEnany joins Republican National Committee as spokesperson|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/kayleigh-mcenany-joins-republican-national-committee-as-spokesperson/article/2630829|accessdate=August 7, 2017|work=The Washington Examiner|date=August 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=RNC>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=gop.com |publisher=Republican National Committee |accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Accepting her appointment, McEnany said in a press release, \"I am excited to be joining the RNC at such an important and historic time in our country. I'm eager to talk about Republican ideas and values and have important discussions about issues affecting Americans across this country.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Kayleigh McEnany Named RNC Spokesperson |url=https://gop.com/kayleigh-mcenany-named-rnc-spokesperson |website=RNC Announcements |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===White House Press Secretary===\nAfter [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] replaced [[Mick Mulvaney]] as White House Chief of Staff in April 2020, Meadows' first personnel change was hiring McEnany as White House Press Secretary on April 7, 2020; which was officially announced the next day.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Singman |first=Brooke |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-names-campaign-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-as-new-white-house-press-secretary |title=Trump names campaign spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany as new White House press secretary |date=April 8, 2020 |work=Fox News |access-date=April 17, 2020 |url-status=live |publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Ltd |last2=Cates |first2=Christopher J |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Stephanie Grisham]], who had served in the role and as [[White House Communications Director]] since June 2019, became [[Melania Trump]]'s chief of staff and spokesperson.<ref>Phillips, Morgan (April 7, 2020). [https://www.foxnews.com/politics/who-is-kayleigh-mcenany-what-to-know-about-incoming-white-house-press-secretary Who is Kayleigh McEnany? What to know about incoming White House press secretary]. ''[[Fox News]]''. Retrieved April 7, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nMcEnany has been critical of the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama presidency]]. In 2017, she mistakenly claimed that President Obama rushed off to a golf game after the 2002 beheading of [[Daniel Pearl]], even though Obama was still a state senator at the time of Pearl's murder. McEnany later apologized for the comment saying she meant to say that Obama went golfing after the 2014 murder of journalist [[James Foley (journalist)|James Foley]] who was beheaded by ISIS in Syria. Obama, who was vacationing on [[Martha's Vineyard]] at the time, admitted that he should have \"anticipated the optics\" of golfing immediately after making a press statement on Foley's death.<ref>[https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tasneemnashrulla/obama-was-golfing-during-pearl-harbor This Trump Surrogate Accused Obama Of Golfing After Daniel Pearl's Murder \u2013 6 Years Before He Was Elected President], BuzzFeed News, 28 march 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Japaridze |first1=Nunu |title=Obama: Golfing after Foley statement was a bad idea |url=https://www.cnn.com/2014/09/07/politics/obama-golfing-optics/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> McEnany also contributed to  the \"[[birther]] movement\" by releasing [[Twitter|tweets]] that referenced President Obama's birth certificate and his half-brother [[Malik Obama]], who lives in [[Kenya]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Klein |first1=Betsy |title=Kayleigh McEnany set to become fourth Trump press secretary |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/07/politics/kayleigh-mcenany-new-white-house-press-secretary/index.html |website=CNN Politics |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMcEnany is a Trump supporter and has defended his actions in the media. As Republican National Committee spokeswoman, she supported Trump in the aftermath of the 2017 [[Charlottesville, Virginia#Conflict over Confederate symbols|conflict over Confederate symbols]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]], when she tweeted \"President @realDonaldTrump once again denounced hate today. The GOP stands behind his message of love and inclusiveness!\" Some media outlets criticized her support of Trump who had blamed multiple parties for the violence that occurred during the [[Unite the Right rally|\"Unite the Right\" rally]] that protested city attempts to remove the statute of [[Robert E. Lee]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwood |first1=Max |title=RNC spokeswoman: GOP stands behind Trump's message 'of love and inclusiveness' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/news/346719-rnc-spokeswoman-the-gop-stands-behind-trumps-message-of-love-and-inclusiveness |website=The Hill |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019, when asked by CNN\u2019s [[Chris Cuomo]] if [[Veracity of statements by Donald Trump|Trump has told lies]], she said: \u201cNo. I don\u2019t believe the president has lied.\u201d When pressed on the topic by Cuomo, she said, \u201cHe doesn\u2019t lie. Guess who lies, the press lies.\u201d She then advised Cuomo to look in the mirror. Cuomo ended the interview.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.my/trump-campaign-spox-cnn-claim-president-has-never-lied-2019-8 A Trump campaign official left a CNN host stunned by claiming Trump has never lied to the American people], Business Insider, 29 August 2019</ref>\n\nIn the weeks prior to her appointment as White House press secretary, McEnany praised Trump's handling of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], saying, \"This president will always put America first, he will always protect American citizens, we will not see diseases like the coronavirus come here, we will not see terrorism come here and isn\u2019t it refreshing when contrasting it with the awful presidency of President Obama.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|last=Smith|first=David|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/07/stephanie-grisham-out-as-trumps-press-secretary-after-never-briefing-the-press|title=Stephanie Grisham out as Trump press secretary after never briefing press|date=2020-04-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In the weeks following her remark, [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|as the virus continued to spread]], McEnany was criticized by many for the comment. McEnany in turn, claimed that she was only speaking in the context of restricting travel to the United States from China.<ref name=\"USA\">{{cite web |last1=Wu |first1=Nicholas |title=New White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany takes heat for past comments on Obama, coronavirus |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/04/08/kayleigh-mcenanys-past-comments-obama-coronavirus/2968413001/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcEnany is married to [[Sean Gilmartin]], a professional [[pitcher|baseball pitcher]] for the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] organization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rays' Sean Gilmartin: Gets camp invite with Rays |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/players/playerpage/1941508/sean-gilmartin |website=CBS Sports |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/mets/ex-met-sean-gilmartin-marries-rnc-spokeswoman-kayleigh-mcenany-article-1.3647275|title=Former Mets pitcher Sean Gilmartin marries RNC spokeswoman Kayleigh McEnany|website=New York Daily News |author1=Ripple, Zachary|date=2017-11-20 |accessdate=2018-01-08|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The couple has one daughter.\n\n== Publications ==\nMcEnany's book, ''The New American Revolution: The Making of a Populist Movement'', was released in early January 2018.<ref name=\"FoxNewsMcEnanyBook\">{{cite web |url= http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/07/michael-wolff-wasn-t-with-trump-on-election-night-those-who-were-prove-his-book-wrong.html |title= Michael Wolff wasn't with Trump on election night. Those who were prove his book wrong |author= Kayleigh McEnany |date= January 8, 2018 |work= [[Fox News]] |accessdate= January 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q27733823|c=Category:Kayleigh McEnany|q=Kayleigh McEnany|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|s=no|wikt=no|species=no}}\n*{{Official website}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephanie Grisham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Press Secretary]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Trump Executive Office}}\n\n{{WHPS}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McEnany, Kayleigh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:Christians from Florida]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Florida Republicans]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Political spokespersons]]\n[[Category:School of Foreign Service alumni]]\n[[Category:White House Press Secretaries]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tampa, Florida]]\n", "name_user": "91.235.97.253", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kayleigh_McEnany"}
